entry.title: Replace WebElement::Form() call by form_util::GetOwningForm().
entry.content:
The WebFormElement used in FormCache::ClearSectionWithElement is used

in a single place, namely as an argument to

form_util::GetAutofillableFormControlElements. That, in turn, calls

GetFormControlElements, which is shadow DOM aware. Therefore the

WebFormElement should also be obtained by using GetOwningForm.



Otherwise, the following scenario would not yield the correct

autofillable form control elements:

- Element is an unassociated form control element inside shadow DOM.

- The shadow host is contained inside a form.



Here the right form to return is the form owning the shadow host. This

is what GetOwningForm does.

entry.title: MojoLPM: introduce MojoLPMGenerator
entry.content:
MojoLPMGenerator aims at simplifying MojoLPM usage by generating some of

the redundant and not interesting bits from a fuzzer developer POV.



This CL introduces multiple things:

1. A new script that is capable of generating both the `.proto` and

corresponding C++ code for generating a MojoLPM fuzzer based on a mojo

interface. The C++ part is simply a `.h` file containing a class that

developer should inherit from in order to remove some of the MojoLPM

boilerplate. See crrev.com/c/5206110 for an example of how this works.

2. A new GN template that helps using this generator. This new template

provides all the existing features of `mojolpm_fuzzer_test`, including

seed corpus handling.



From a fuzzer developer POV, the structure of the proto file doesn't

matter, except if using a seed corpus. In that case, this doesn't change

much from the existing way MojoLPM works, since the internal structure

must be known to the developer in order to be able to write corpus

files.



Fuzzer developer would only need to override the "new" method for the

mojom interface they wish to fuzz. Even if the mojo interface was to

change, this bit will remain, independently of the mojo interface

structure.



Bug: 1483992

entry.title: Implement DOM Clobbering use counters
entry.content:
This change introduces new UseCounters to understand the usage of

patterns that lead to DOM Clobbering. Four new counters are implemented:



- kDOMClobberedShadowedDocumentPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedNotShadowedDocumentPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedShadowedFormPropertyAccessed

- kDOMClobberedNotShadowedFormPropertyAccessed



First two are meant to count usage of DOM Clobbering on document. For

example: would create a new property: document.abc.

We distinguish whether this property name would shadow an existing

property or not.



The latter two count usage of DOM Clobbering on forms. Similarly to

document, we also distinguish between shadowed and non-shadowed

properties.



These UseCounters will help make a decision on whether we can disable

some flavors of DOM Clobbering by default.



Also this CL changes the name of existing counter:

kDOMClobberedVariableAccessed -> kDOMClobberedWindowPropertyAccessed



to make it more consistent with the other counters.

entry.title: [Mullhet] Fix password form preview.
entry.content:
Previously landed CLs crrev.com/c/5307518 and crrev.com/c/5307397

changed the password form preview UX behavior. The root cause of the

change is that:

* PAA::FillPasswordSuggestion is called when the user accepts the

suggestion. This overwrites the previewed suggested value.

* PAA::ClearPreviewedForm is called when the Autofill popup is closed.

This call is done after the call to PAA::FillPasswordSuggestion. This

function is a no-op if the fields' suggested values are empty.



Before crrev.com/c/5307518, the password form preview was never cleared

because of the behavior described above. After the CL, the preview

was cleared after the fields are filled. That's why the lost blue

background highlighting.



The solution is to clear preview in PAA::FillPasswordSuggestion as it

is done in the AutofillAgent. This CL also removes

PreviewInfo::prefix_length because it's not needed to implement the

observed behavior.



PAA = PasswordAutofillAgent

entry.title: Reland "Update last interacted form when JS modifies a field's value"
entry.content:
This is a reland (with changes) of crrev.com/c/5238376 whose description is linked below. The CL was reverted for causing regressions in

speedometer2 (links to the numbers in the reverted CL).



Regression (of the reverted CL):

3.5% regression of speedometer2 on android-pixel4-perf.



To optimize this and overcome the regression, some profiling of

speedometer2 was done and it was found that:

- HTMLInputElement::setValueForBinding is called ~240k times.

- HTMLInputElement::setCheckedForBinding is called ~300k times. Which

is super wasteful since Autofill currently completely ignores

checkboxes.

- HTML[Select|SelectList|TextArea]Element::setValueForBinding aren't

called.



This CL therefore:

- Removes support for notifying autofill of JS changes to checkbox

elements, saving lots of unnecessary calls to Autofill.

- Moves the `old_value == new_value` check to blink, to avoid calling

`element.Value()` since it is already available there and save a few

trivial function calls.

- Early returns if autofill is not tracking any element for submission,

which saves the need to uselessly compute owning forms and checking

feature state.

- Moves feature state checking last in

AutofillAgent::JavaScriptChangedValue since it might hide other

regressions caused by GetOwningForm.

- Replaces re-extraction, which is a full DOM traversal, by a few state

updates, in order to avoid future regressions when the logic is not

gated by a disabled feature anymore.



Results of this CL:

Same CL lands with no visible changes (maybe very minor improvements?)

on speedometer2 on various platforms (linked in the change log of this

CL [Patchset 11])



Original change's description:

> Update last interacted form when JS modifies a field's value

>

> Autofill is currently working on replacing the observer it uses for

> disappearing elements by a direct blink connection notifying of

> removals and hiding of elements.

>

> Some notification about hidden elements are provided to Autofill

> during style recalc (e.g. changing visibility attribute to 'hidden')

> and during this Autofill is not allowed to query the focusability of

> a node.

>

> This causes a problem for Autofill: When submission is inferred,

> Autofill tries to extract the form of the element it was tracking, and

> part of this is querying the focusability of fields. Which means that

> if submission is inferred from a notification sent during style

> recalc, Autofill is not allowed to extract a form at submission time.

>

> The alternative is to use the provisionally saved form, which is a

> form that Autofill updates on autofill operations and user edits. In

> this context, form means either an HTML
tagged section or the

> collection of all unowned control elements.

>

> This CL tries to make the provisionally saved form approach the state

> of the extracted form at submission time (should we have extracted it)

> by also updating it on JS changes. To achieve that, we modify the

> signal JavaScriptChangedAutofilledValue to JavaScriptChangedValue.

>

> Note that this update is only performed if JS modifies the form that

> is already tracked by autofill. Which means that only user edits and

> autofill (also user triggered) have permission to change the form

> tracked by autofill from one form to another, but JS only has

> permission to update the currently tracked form.

>

> The CL also adds logic to default to the provisionally save form

> unconditionally at submission time instead of extraction.

>

> All behavior changes are gated behind a feature flag.

>

entry.title: [//cc] Change HeadsUpLayerDisplay to calculate texture_target internally
entry.content:
HeadsUpLayerDisplayImpl currently gets the texture target that it uses

from RasterCapabilities::texture_target. This in turn is computed by

LayerTreeHostImpl as follows [1]:

* If the resource is an overlay candidate, gpu::GetBufferTextureTarget()

passing SCANOUT and the BufferFormat corresponding to the tile's SIF

* Otherwise, GL_TEXTURE_2D



This CL changes HeadsUpLayerDisplayImpl to calculate the texture target

at the point that it needs it using the GpuBacking's SharedImage. That

SharedImage's format was passed in as the format of the resource at

creation time [2], and the format of the resource was itself taken from

the tile format [3]. The ClientSharedImage's usage will have SCANOUT iff

the backing is an overlay candidate [4] (which in turn comes directly

from the raster caps [5]), and ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget()

will return GL_TEXTURE_2D if SCANOUT is passed but the CSI doesn't have

SCANOUT in its own usage. Hence, the behavior is unchanged. To validate

that, we add a CHECK() that the computed value is the same (we will

remove the check when we remove RasterCapabilities storing the texture

target entirely).



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/trees/layer_tree_host_impl.cc;l=2919-2958?q=layer_tree_host_impl&ss=chromium

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/layers/heads_up_display_layer_impl.cc;l=326-330?q=heads_up_display&ss=chromium

[3] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/layers/heads_up_display_layer_impl.cc;l=304-305;drc=f4a00cc248dd2dc8ec8759fb51620d47b5114090;bpv=1;bpt=1

[4] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/layers/heads_up_display_layer_impl.cc;l=323-325?q=heads_up_dis&ss=chromium

[5] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:cc/layers/heads_up_display_layer_impl.cc;l=311;drc=f4a00cc248dd2dc8ec8759fb51620d47b5114090;bpv=1;bpt=1

entry.title: [//media] Convert VideoResourceUpdater's computing texture target
entry.content:
This CL converts VideoResourceUpdater from computing the texture target

to use via gpu::GetBufferTextureTarget() to instead using

ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget(). Whereas the former was called

only when the SI was an overlay candidate and otherwise left

`texture_target_` at its default value of GL_TEXTURE_2D, the latter can

be called unconditionally as it deliberately returns GL_TEXTURE_2D when

the ClientSI doesn't have SCANOUT usage (as the ClientSI here won't if

it is not an overlay candidate).



NOTE: A more ambitious line of work could look to remove

VideoResourceUpdater::texture_target() altogether in favor of obtaining

it from the ClientSharedImage as needed. However, that's out of scope of

this CL (and the line of work looking to consolidate the codebase

around ClientSharedImage::GetTextureTarget()).

entry.title: Add basic overall arrow key navigation to Picker using "pseudo focus".
entry.content:
Focus generally stays on the Picker search field while the Picker is

open, to allow users to easily type and modify their search query. So,

to implement key navigation, we use "pseudo focus" which makes Picker

items look and behave as if they were focused without having actual

focus.



This CL adds various plumbing to handle arrow key navigation using

this "pseudo focus", mainly:



1. Add PickerPseudoFocusHandler interface which is implemented by each

Picker page (zero state page, category page, search results page).

2. Pass key events via PickerKeyEventHandler to handle pseudo focus.



Note that this doesn't interact properly with tab key traversal and

pseudo focus is missing accessibility announcements. Followups will

handle these issues.

entry.title: [Files]: Simplify ARC recent source code.
entry.content:
ARC recent source uses an approach where the ARC recent source owns a

number of roots. When asking for ARC recent files we then ask all roots

for recent files and once they are done, return them. However, this

makes stopping the ARC recent source more complex. In this solution

rather than having one ARC recent source that owns 3 ARC media roots,

the recent model owns directly 3 ARC recent source initialized to point

to Documents, Images, and Videos. Stopping those is as simple as

stopping RecentDiskSource.

entry.content:
This is the beginning of Phase 2 of moving DIPS from //chrome to

//content (see go/dips-move).



To break dependencies on //chrome, we create a new interface for Content

Embedders to implement: DipsDelegate. ChromeDipsDelegate is a subclass

which will maintain the current behavior in Chrome.



Eventually we will get a pointer to DipsDelegate via

ContentBrowserClient, but that isn't accessible from //chrome. So for

now we temporarily defined ChromeDipsDelegate::GetInstance() to get it.



This CL defines the first method: GetEngagedSites(). The default

implementation returns no sites. ChromeDipsDelegate's override queries

the SiteEngagementService for all sites with any engagement (which was

the previous behavior).



There should be no change in behavior with this CL.
